[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Nvidia just released a brand new AI tool that can convert an image into an interactive city. And Google has announced a brand new AI screenwriting tool that looks crazy impressive. We have all of that and more in today\'s'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'episode of AI film news. Thank you so much for watching. My name\'s Caleb. Be sure to like and subscribe if you want more training and tutorials directly here on the platform. So, let\'s kick things off by talking about the big news'

[00:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'from Nvidia. It seems like just about every single day there\'s big news from Nvidia. The big featured story that I want to talk about is a new tool called LERNA 2. This tool essentially can take an input starting image, turn it into a'

[00:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '3D world. From that 3D world, you can shoot video exploring the brand new 3D world and it will reverse engineer all of the 3D geometry based on what it creates. Long story short, you can take'

[00:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'input image, create a very very large 3D world, and then from there connect it with other AI systems like the Isaac Sim model inside Nvidia to interact with'

[01:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that 3D world. It\'s kind of similar to Genie 3, but you get way more information and 3D rendering capabilities. They also released an interactive demo on Hugging Face that you should have access to by the time we'

[01:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'are watching this video. On the website, there\'s some pretty cool use cases. For example, we have this 3D scan here of this home and you can see that they can take the 3D information that LERNA 2 is'

[01:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'able to generate, run it through the Isaac Sim model at Nvidia, and begin to have interactive environments that you can explore. So, in this case, you can see you\'re able to actually go inside'

[01:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the home and explore it using AI interactions. Now, obviously Nvidia leans very heavily beyond just the creative applications. Of course, being able to utilize this for robotic simulations and all sorts of other'

[01:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'really impressive, futuristic, sci-fi techniques is really interesting. But, I think one of the biggest takeaways in having more world generation tools like this coming into the market is the fact that it really fundamentally changes the'

[02:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'way in which we approach our stories. Right now, if you want to create an AI video, more than likely you are going to either create a simple 3D scene and shoot images and animate those images'

[02:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'using an AI video tool, or you\'re going to use some sort of omni reference feature to upload your assets and generate your video as an output. The problem is you lose a lot of information when it comes to consistency with your'

[02:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'environments and ultimately helping you to create the world in which your AI story is living. Having 3D tools like this available to us and then giving us the ability to go in and direct and edit changes to that environment is going to'

[02:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'allow us to essentially create a 3D set environment. We\'ll be able to move our camera around the scene, prompt for the characters and the action that we want to happen, and then go in and move our'

[02:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'camera around and ultimately tell our story. This is the future of AI filmmaking and we\'re just now scratching the surface of what is possible. I highly recommend going and checking this out for yourself. And not to be outdone,'

[03:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the team at Tencent Hunyuan, which are the people that create Minimax, also came out with their own version of a 3D world tool. You have the ability to upload an image and create a 3D world in'

[03:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'return. It\'s open source and should be live by the time you are watching this video. And again, it just reinforces the thing that we talk about almost on a daily basis here inside Curious Refuge. And that\'s that open source tools are'

[03:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'right behind the closed public-facing tools that you must pay credits for. The fact that all of these open source tools are able to produce results that cost tens of millions of dollars just a few'

[03:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'months ago is frankly crazy impressive. And the final bit of world generation news that I want to talk about inside of this episode comes from World Labs who creates basically the underlying'

[04:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'architecture behind a lot of the image to 3D world applications that you can run inside of common aggregators today. They came out with a render engine which is called Spark 2 and it basically allows you to interact with these 3D'

[04:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'worlds in a way that is much more scalable for an online environment. Now, you can go over to the research paper and check out some of these 3D environments for yourself, but there\'s a couple that I\'m really excited to show'

[04:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you here. The first is this 3D world of Hobbiton. So, this is running inside of Spark 2 and we can go inside of I don\'t think this is Bilbo\'s home, but you have the ability to explore the Hobbit hole'

[04:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and just kind of like walk around and there\'s a lot of 3D information here. You can see it did a really good job. And is this a hot tub inside the Hobbit hole here? I guess I missed this detail'

[04:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'inside The Lord of the Rings, but you know what? Good for the Hobbits for knowing how to lean into self-care. Now, the other thing that makes this really interesting is allegedly this tool has the ability to simulate an entire city.'

[05:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, we have this example here from San Francisco and you can see that as we zoom in here it is able to render out some pretty decent fidelity and you can zoom out to a city view. You can zoom in'

[05:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'super close and then get close to some of these buildings and it takes some time to render. So, I don\'t think that this is necessarily real time, but the fact that it\'s able to composite all of these elements together into a scale the'

[05:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'size of a city is frankly really impressive. It\'s a common trope in sci-fi crime thrillers where the person is inside some sort of research room and they get a video or an image and they'

[05:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'say, "Zoom in on that. Enhance. Enhance. Enhance." Well, well, that was futuristic technology, but this new white paper called Wonder Zoom is looking at to fix that problem. Basically, you have the ability to input'

[05:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'an image and you can infinitely zoom on any aspect of that image and it uses generative AI to enhance the details. Now, are those details crazy accurate to the inputted reference image and can you'

[06:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'pull a license plate that is just a couple of pixels? Probably not, but the fact that you have the ability to do that using this tool or even a system where you simply up res it yourself is'

[06:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'really helpful, especially if you don\'t have all of the image or video angles that you need for telling your story. Enrollment in the brand new Curious Refuge membership experience is now open over at Curious Refuge. As of today, we'

[06:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'have officially launched our one-on-one artist calls along with applications to our distinguished network of artist program designed to help you land real-world opportunities. You can learn'

[06:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'more and find out more information by visiting Curious Refuge. We just hosted our weekly virtual office hours with the community and had a blast. We would love to have you inside the program. We came across a pretty interesting workflow'

[06:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'using Seed Dance this last week from Christopher, where basically he created a scene using Seed Dance, but for whatever reason at the end of it, we have this random character that walks into the scene. So, in the actual scene,'

[07:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'we don\'t want that man to just randomly come behind the pole. We want to remove him. Well, you actually can use Seed Dance to pull this off. Let me show you how it\'s done. So, for our starting image, I have this video clip of this'

[07:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'man walking down a hallway in an office. This was generated using Nano Banana 2. And we\'re going to drag and drop it into our start frame section. I\'m using Free Pick, but of course you can use any'

[07:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'video aggregator of your choice. And for the prompt, we\'re basically just going to have the man walk down the hallway. We\'ll make sure we have SeaDance 2.0 selected. The resolution'

[07:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'will be 720p unfortunately cuz that is as big as it gets. And we\'ll change the duration to 15 seconds, aspect ratio to 16 by 9, and go ahead and hit generate. And after just one clip, we have this'

[07:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'video here. Okay. So, you can see we randomly just have this woman walking into the background. Let\'s say that we want to'

[08:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'remove her. Well, you could totally use Free Pick again and just upload your video clip into the video section and ask the AI model to remove the character from the background. But, I actually want to show you how to do the same'

[08:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'thing inside of Runway. They actually integrated SeaDance 2.0 directly inside of Runway this last week, and I think it\'s kind of fascinating. So, let\'s hop in. So, I\'m on the Runway platform. I\'m going to go to video here, and you can'

[08:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'see we can upload assets here whether they\'re images or videos. Basically, we\'re going to use the Omni model inside of SeaDance. So, let\'s go ahead and bring in our original footage. We\'ll drop that into the plus icon there. And'

[08:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'for our prompt, we\'ll keep it crazy simple. We\'ll say remove the woman walking out of the room at 14 seconds, and we\'ll make sure we\'re running in the SeaDance 2.0 model. I should note that this says multimodal using SeaDance 2.0.'

[09:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'We have found that there is a quality difference depending on if you upload video footage versus just an image alone because there are technically multiple models running under the surface. But,'

[09:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'for the sake of ease, we\'ll just say these are both SeaDance 2.0 and go ahead and hit generate. Now, what\'s so interesting is whenever we utilize the same techniques that we saw online, it actually took us about eight shots to'

[09:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'get the shot that we\'re looking for. So, we had quite a few fails where it just continued to have the woman in the background. And so, it is going to be an iterative process to get what you\'re'

[09:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'looking for, but in the end we got to this video clip here. And you can see the woman is now removed from the background. Now, that all does come at a cost. So, you may notice that'

[09:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in the background here, there\'s a bit of distortion happening in some of the reflections. There\'s just some like kind of wonkiness going on. So, in most cases I would say it\'s better to generate the base footage to be exactly what you\'re'

[10:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'looking for, rather than having to go back and forth because every time you have to go back and forth and upload video footage and change the environment, you\'re going to have some quality loss and it\'s going to cost you just a lot more money ultimately. For'

[10:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'every generation, it cost us about $4. So, if it takes us eight generations to get what we\'re looking for, that\'s 32 bucks. So, that\'s going to add up really quickly. But, all of that being said, I noticed that inside of Runway, they'

[10:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'actually are allowing you to generate with SeeDance in the unlimited model. It\'s not saying if it\'s SeeDance fast or SeeDance Pro, but the fact that it\'s $95 a month and hypothetically you get'

[10:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'unlimited video generations using SeeDance and other video models is actually pretty compelling. So, I recommend checking it out for yourself, and if you run into any usage limits, be sure to let us know. Last week, we'

[10:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'talked about a brand new AI video model that says it\'s as good as SeeDance 2.0. And I\'m talking about my favorite video model name ever, Happy Horse. Happy Horse has now been confirmed as a video'

[11:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'generation model from the people at Alibaba. And if you go over to LM Arena, they actually are already ranking Happy Horse as the very best AI tool for AI video editing. Now, that\'s a preliminary'

[11:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'test, and I\'m not entirely sure exactly how you\'re testing a model that is not publicly available yet, but the fact is it\'s going to be very powerful and hypothetically open source. So, I\'m very'

[11:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'curious to hop into this tool once it drops. The team at Midjourney has released Midjourney 1.8, which is a much-needed improvement to Midjourney 8.0 alpha, which frankly was a pretty'

[11:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'big disappointment when we announced it just a few weeks ago. Midjourney 8.1 has native 2K HD rendering. It\'s three times faster than the previous version of'

[11:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Midjourney 8, and the model is allegedly faster and better quality across the board. But, let\'s not take their word for it. Let\'s hop into the tool and find out for ourselves. So, I\'m here on the Midjourney alpha website. You will have'

[12:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to click the link below this video to hop over to this alpha version, and we\'ll do a few different prompts that we tested a few weeks ago. We\'ll say a cinematic still of a man wearing a sci-fi mech suit in a futuristic market'

[12:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'surrounded by blue gems, and you can see over on the right side we have Midjourney version 8.1. And let\'s change the aspect ratio to generate. And after a few seconds, we have this image here.'

[12:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And again, stylistically, Midjourney tends to be the very best tool on the market for generating the overall look and feel of your film or creative project. I think'

[12:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it\'s so much better than Nano Banana Pro or Flux or any of the other more popular image models. This just looks very high-end and cinematic. It did a really good job, and if we compare that against'

[12:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'version 8, version 8 gave us this, so 8.1 is just a huge huge improvement. Now, we also prompted for an orb with the words find the stone inside, and it generated this. I do think that middle'

[13:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'finger looks a little too big. Midjourney is maybe struggling a bit with finger generation even still, but if we compare it against version 8, again, 8.1 is just so so much better. We'

[13:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'also generated this image of a snorkeler coming across a giant squid, which apparently has eyes that are as big as a basketball. Had no idea. That\'s kind of terrifying. And the same thing was'

[13:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'generated inside of version 8. Again, version 8 just does not look realistic. It comes across a bit more like concept art as opposed to something deeply cinematic and interesting. And then finally, we wanted to test out a graphic'

[13:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'design concept. And so we created this poster for Cosmic Sushi in version 8.1, which it looks okay. Maybe a bit more like clip art. It definitely is coming across as AI generated because it\'s a'

[14:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'little too perfect, but it\'s not terrible. And last time we tested the tool, we generated this in version 8. And in this case, I actually do like the version from Midjourney 8 better because it is a bit more imperfect. It just'

[14:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'comes across as a bit more hand-drawn and custom. It looks really good, but again, it\'s all about iteration and generating a ton of shots to get exactly what you\'re looking for. The team at Google has announced a screenwriting tool called Google Fabula that looks'

[14:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'pretty interesting. There\'s not an online demo that you can play around with just yet, but from what we can see, the tool actually works in three parts.'

[14:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The first part is you have the ability to upload your characters, your scene, and just the overall story that you are working with. Essentially, you can upload a treatment on the left. In the middle, you have the ability to break'

[14:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'down the individual story beats that you\'re trying to get to. This would be the sticky notes on the whiteboard that get rearranged during the writing process. That is happening right in the middle of the actual application. And on the right, you have the actual script'

[15:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that is generated. So it kind of is simulating the writing process all entirely inside of a single tool. Now, they actually have an announcement video that you can check out online. What\'s'

[15:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'also fascinating is this announcement video was uploaded 7 months ago, so they\'ve been sitting on this for a while, but I think this could have huge implications for the screenwriting process. For a company like Google to'

[15:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'try to get into the world of screenwriting and create an end-to-end tool, I think this is really compelling because a lot of the creative innovations and tools that we use on a day-to-day basis are already running'

[15:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'from Google. So, rather than having to go to an outside tool, hypothetically, the Google system could stitch everything together. Whether you\'re generating images with Nano Banana Pro or video with Google VIO or even'

[16:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'stitching them all together in an intelligent way using embedding 2, it seems like Google is probably going to be the tool that brings everything together. And so, I think announcements like this make it really exciting and'

[16:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'hint that the future of creativity is going to be dramatically changed in the coming months. Now, speaking of Google, they also released a brand new text-to-voice model that I think is'

[16:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'really compelling and it really changes and solves one of the fundamental problems that you have whenever you\'re using a voice tool like 11 Labs. Let me show you how to use it. The tool is'

[16:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'called Gemini 3.1 Flash TTS Preview. I think that we should really stick to the barnyard theme we have with Happy Horse, so maybe this is like Indignant Pig or something like that. Or even Nano Banana, that\'s a great name, too. I\'m'

[16:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I\'m really open to some fun naming conventions here, but yeah, 3.1 Flash TTS is what we have for now. Now, of course, the takeaway is you can copy and paste the text and then just go ahead and run and it will generate the speech. But I think what\'s interesting about TTS'

[17:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is it takes one step further in the process of actually directing the voices. So, for our example, I\'m going to select a voice here. So, we\'ll go to Algenib here and let\'s listen to his default voice.'

[17:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; What\'s a skill you\'d like to develop? &gt;&gt; Okay, cool. So, we will select him as the character. And we have our text here. But the cool thing is you can define the scene and the context in which your character is speaking. So,'

[17:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'for our scene, we can say a man is at a conference announcing a new tool. And for the context, we can say he just concluded the big keynote inside his presentation. And now he is announcing Google 3.1 Flash TTS. And we\'ll go ahead'

[17:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and click run. Let\'s listen to the result. &gt;&gt; Introducing Gemini 3.1 Flash TTS, our latest text-to-speech model with scene direction, speaker level specificity,'

[17:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'audio tags, more natural plus expressive voices, and support for 70 different languages. &gt;&gt; Okay, so yeah, that was a lot of enthusiasm. But that voice is what I would say very much in line with a lot'

[18:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of the announcements that you hear at these conferences. NAB has been happening and I imagine there\'s a lot of announcements that sound exactly like this. Now, that\'s fine for marketing material, but what I think this is'

[18:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'really interesting for is actually creating really emotive characters for your stories. So, let\'s test this out. So, for our new scene, I\'m going to say a man is breaking up with his girlfriend. He is sad. And for the'

[18:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'context, he\'s sad, he\'s emotive, he\'s sitting at a dinner table, right? He\'s uh you know, just going through a hard time here. And for whatever reason, the breakup line is the announcement about Google Flash TTS. So, let\'s go ahead and'

[18:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'run. &gt;&gt; Introducing Gemini 3.1 Flash TTS, our latest text-to-speech model specificity, audio tags, more natural'

[19:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'plus expressive voices, and support for 70 different languages. &gt;&gt; So, it did a great job there. Now, of'

[19:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'course, let\'s compare this against 11 Labs, which has kind of been the industry level tool up to this point. So, I\'m inside 11 Labs here and to create context in 11 Labs, all you have to do is create an open square bracket'

[19:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'here and I\'m just going to put in sad. So, the delivery should be sad and we\'re using the 11 Labs version 3 model here and I have just a a voice that\'s kind of this crime and horror narrator. In a'

[19:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'similar vein to the character that we have from Google. So, let\'s go ahead and hit generate. &gt;&gt; Introducing Gemini 3.1 Flash TTS, our latest text-to-speech model with scene direction, speaker-level specificity,'

[19:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'audio tags, more natural plus expressive voices, and support for 70 different languages. &gt;&gt; Okay, you can see yeah, the tonality is'

[20:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'sad, but it\'s really not on the same planet as the voices that were generated from Google. And I think that this hints to something larger. Whenever we are working with actors, when we\'re directing our scene, we don\'t typically'

[20:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'communicate via tags, we communicate via context and natural language. That\'s the directorial process is communicating at not only the performance that you want to see, but also the larger context to help create the overall performance. And'

[20:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I think having the ability to add in that context inside of our tools is just really, really powerful. There have been quite a few stories over the last couple of weeks in the larger Hollywood ecosystem. The first comes from The'

[20:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Hollywood Reporter, who actually went into a deep dive into the way in which jobs have changed in the last few years and they\'ve realized that a lot of the transformations are not the result of'

[20:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'artificial intelligence and in fact, positions like writers and artists are actually more in demand in this new AI era. We came across a story about how Doug Liman is actually working on a $70'

[21:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'million feature that features actors like Gal Gadot and Casey Affleck who are utilizing generative AI to create the environments. We\'ve seen a lot of'

[21:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'generative AI use for a virtual production environment to help save on overall production cost and they said that they\'re actually going to be taking this to Can to potentially get a buyer. So, I think it\'s very interesting and'

[21:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the topic is all about the history of Bitcoin and so, of course, that is just kind of the perfect pairing for creating a really compelling film. And the final bit of news that I think is really fascinating is Milla Jovovich has'

[21:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'actually been a founding member of an AI startup initiative called Mem Palace that\'s designed to have permanent memory to the information that AI keeps about you. It basically creates an organized'

[21:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'data structure that allows AI systems to intelligently go in and explore the data as if it\'s a palace. It\'s really interesting to see a lot of high-end celebrities investing in a lot of these'

[22:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'AI tools. What I don\'t know is if you work with an API to access the memory palace, does it actually need a multi-pass? There are a lot of AI events popping up around the industry. We have'

[22:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'an AI filmmaking meetup happening in Palm Beach on April 16th. We\'re hosting an online workshop about building your portfolio in this new AI era on April 21st. And we\'re hosting an AI filmmaking'

[22:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'meetup on April 23rd out here in Los Angeles. If you happen to be in the area, we would love to see you there. And that brings us to our AI films of the week. The first film that I want to'

[22:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'shout out is a prologue to The Chronicles of Bone by Cabin the Kid who is the instructor of our advanced AI filmmaking course. It has great pacing, sound design, the style is just'

[23:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'incredible. And I should note that we are releasing advanced AI filmmaking 2.0 in the very near future. That is going to be taught by Kevin. If you want to learn more, you can find a link below this video. The next project I want to'

[23:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'shout out is a spec project created as a Snickers commercial from Christopher Schlurf. And I think he did an amazing job. It has a great twist at the end. It looks really high-end. Amazing work on'

[23:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the project. And the final film that I want to shout out is called The Sister, created by JS Films. What I like about this is not only the quality of the film looks really nice, but he also hopped in'

[23:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and did a breakdown of his process. And so, at the end of the film, you can see how he pulled it off. And I think it\'s just really helpful whenever artists work together to share information like this. Thank you so much for watching'

